 Raymond Williams and Fredric Jameson, brings Chicano literature into the arena of contemporary literary theory. By focusing on an important but little-studied poetic tradition, his book challenges our ideas of the American canon and extends the reach of Hispanists and folklorists as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican poetryxMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican poetryxMexican influences. 0aBallads, SpanishxAppreciationzMexicozUnited States. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aMexican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aSocial problems in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  a1960s.  a1970s.  aamerican literature.  aamerican poetry.  aart.  aartistic influences.  aballad poetry.  aballads.  achicano poetry.  achicano.  acorrido.  afolklore.  aharold bloom.  alife story.  aliterary analysis.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary influences.  aliterary theory.  aliterature.  amarxism.  amarxist.  amexican border.  amexico.  aoral tradition.  apoetics.  apoetry in spanish.  apoetry.  apolitical.  apolitics.  araymond williams.  asocial studies.  aspanish poetry.  atrue story.  awestern poetry.  awestern world.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091187140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520911871423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520911871/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY